<div>
  <h2>
    <b
      >Cross-reactivity in ChIP is no longer a problem with the use of
      SNAP-ChIP<sup>®</sup> certified antibodies</b
    >
  </h2>

  <p>
    SNAP-ChIP certified antibodies must exhibit cross-reactivity to related PTMs
    less than 20%. For example, an antibody to a lysine methylation state (<i
      >e.g.</i
    >
    H3K4me1) is tested against EpiCypher's full SNAP-ChIP<sup>®</sup>
    K-MetStat<sup>™</sup> panel containing unmodified, me1, me2, and me3 states
    at 5 lysine sites: H3K4, H3K9, H3K27, H3K36, and H4K20 (examples shown
    below), enabling assessment of antibody specificity relative to the most
    likely sources of cross-reactivity (<i>e.g.</i> mono-, di-, and tri-methyl
    states) and the most widely studied histone methylation PTMs
    <i><u>directly</u></i> in your ChIP experiment. If even a single species in
    the panel exhibits cross-reactivity above 20% (Figure below right), we do
    not recommended the use of these antibodies for ChIP studies.
  </p>

  <p>
    <span style="color: orange !important;"
      ><b
        >We can help you to start using SNAP-ChIP as internal control for your
        experiments,</b
      ></span
    >
    contact us at
    <a href="mailto:info@epicypher.com"><u>info@epicypher.com</u></a>
  </p>

  <p style="text-align: center;">
